ce:section.ce:para:
The MTT assays were employed for the investigation of in-vitro cytotoxicity of the synthesized N-CDs. For cytotoxicity studies, the L-929 (Mouse fibroblast cell line) and MCF-7 (human breast adenocarcinoma cell line) were used. Fig. 10
                         shows the microscopic images of different concentrations (0, 5, 10, 15, 20 and 25 μL) of N-CDs incubated with L-929 and MCF-7 cells for 24 h. From the images of MCF-7 cells (Fig. 11
                        ), it could be seen that the synthesized N-CDs exhibit minimum level of anticancer potential on MCF-7 cells. But in the case of L-929 cells, it could be found that the synthesized N-CDs did not affect the L-929 normal cells compared to that of MCF-7 cancer cells. This was confirmed by counting the viable cells in both cell wells. The cell viability was found to be <90% (Fig. 12
                        ) in L-929 cells and the cell viability was <80% in MCF-7 cells (Fig. 13
                        ), even at higher concentration (25 μL/mL) of N-CDs. The result revealed that, the synthesized N-CDs did not cause any effect on the viability of L-929 cells (Fig. 10). Infact, the N-CDs showed higher cytotoxicity on MCF-7 cells (Fig. 11). The synthesized N-CDs were found to have more cell death in MCF-7 cells when compared to L-929 cells and this indicates the target selective activity of the prepared N-CDs. Finally, it is confirmed that the cytotoxicity activity on L-929 cells follows passive diffusion mechanism and the anticancer activity on MCF-7 cells occurred due to the receptor-mediated endocytosis mechanism of prepared N-CDs [64].
